-- Zijin Must Close Its Shanghang Copper Plant on Pollution: China Week Ahead
-- Bloomberg News
-- 2010-07-19T00:29:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-19/zijin-must-close-its-shanghang-copper-plant-on-pollution-china-week-ahead.html

          
          
             Zijin Mining Group Co. said it must
close its Shanghang copper plant in southeastern China’s Fujian
province after a waste water leakage poisoned a major waterway.  
 A plant manager, deputy plant manager and environmental
safety officer were detained by police, Zijin said in a
statement to the Hong Kong Stock Exchange today. The Fujian
provincial government will take legal action against the Zijin
executives, China’s state news agency Xinhua  said on July 16 .  
 China’s  interest-rate swaps  dropped to a one-year low on
July 16 as a slowdown in economic growth prompted investors to
speculate policy makers will favor borrowing costs that support
the recovery.  
 Gross domestic product  grew 10.3 percent in the second
quarter, compared with an 11.9 percent gain in the previous
three months, the statistics bureau said yesterday. The central
bank allowed the yield on three-year bills to drop 3 basis
points to 2.65 percent at a July 15 auction, the first decline
in six weeks.  
 Government bonds advanced last week on banks’ rising demand
for debt after a cash shortage eased.  The yield  on the 3.25
percent note due in May 2020 dropped 6 basis points to 3.28
percent, and the price of the security rose 0.51 per 100 yuan
face amount to 99.70, the funding center data showed.  
 China’s yuan climbed against the dollar in two weeks as
signs the U.S. economy is losing momentum bolstered demand for
the local currency.  
 Yuan Little Changed  
 The yuan was little changed last week, rising 0.05 percent
on Friday to 6.7750 per U.S. dollar, from 6.7785 on Thursday,
according to the China Foreign Exchange Trade System.  
 The Shanghai Composite Index fell 1.9 percent last week to
2,424.27, slumping by the most in two weeks after July 15
economic data trailed estimates.  
 Most China stocks rose on Friday, led by consumer-related
companies, as investors sought resilient earnings prospects
after economic growth slowed.  
 Wuliangye Yibin Co. and Bright Dairy & Food Co. gained more
than 3 percent among food and beverage companies. Zijin Mining
Group Co. dropped 5.4 percent after it said three managers were
detained by the police following an acid spill. Agricultural
Bank of China Ltd. lost 0.4 percent in Shanghai as it debuted in
Hong Kong on July 16. The CSI 300 Index gained 0.3 percent to
2,616.13.  
